04514nam a22006855i 9781477303412DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211989txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773034127 a10.7560/7650302doi  a(DE-B1597)586967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPS3511.A86bZ98535 1987 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.522191 aWatson, James G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWilliam Faulkner, Letters & Fictions /cJames G. Watson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1989  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations Used -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. The Two Canons -- tII. Crossings -- tIII. Integrated Letters -- tIV. Letters at Hand -- tV. Broken Letters -- tVI. Personal Distances: The Public Man of Letters -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBesides the groundbreaking novels and stories that brought him fame, William Faulkner throughout his life wrote letters—to his publisher, his lovers, his family, and his friends. In this first major study of epistolarity in Faulkner's work, James G. Watson examines Faulkner's personal correspondence as a unique second canon of writing, separate from his literary canon with its many fictional letters but developing along parallel lines. By describing the similarity of forms and conventions in Faulkner's personal and fictional correspondence, Watson clearly demonstrates that Faulkner's personal experience as a writer of letters significantly shaped his imaginative work early and late. Letters are always about themselves; they re-create a world between the sender and the receiver. In this illuminating study, Faulkner's personal letters are treated as a form of reflexive writing: first-person narratives in which Sender self-consciously portrays Self to a specific Receiver, likewise portrayed in the letter-text. This duality of actual experience and imaginative re-creation measures the personal distances between the life of the writer and the written self-image. It reveals that letters are at once fragments of autobiography and fictions of self. Such "laws of letters" apply equally to the letters that appear throughout Faulkner's novels and stories. The twenty-one letters and telegrams in The Sound and the Fury, for example, portray character, propel plot, and convey important themes of failed communication and broken identity. From Soldiers' Pay to his last work, Faulkner's carefully lettered canon of fiction is dramatic evidence of his understanding of epistolarity and of the extent to which he adapted letters, including some of his own, to shape his fictional world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAmerican lettersxHistory and criticism. 0aEpistolary fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aEpistolary fiction, American--History and criticism. 0aImaginary lettersxHistory and criticism. 0aLetter writing in literature. 0aLetters in literature. 0aNovelists, Americany20th centuryvCorrespondence. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aWatson, James G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477303412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477303412/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK